    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. So it's all about that head-dependency relationship. I'm just struggling with the visual part of it. When I'm looking at these massive trees with all these branches going on in every direction, it's hard to keep track of the paths. How can I tell if a specific branch has wandered off or if there's an error in the way the sub-nodes are branching out from the main trunk?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Visualizing deep trees is tough, but you need to introduce some organizational structure, like a strong, clear path for your gaze. Think of it like a labyrinth designed by a very organized architect—you need clear markers.\n\nTo track a specific branch, always follow the head-dependency rule backward. Start at the lowest element, say a prepositional phrase (PP), and ask: \"What is the head of this PP?\" Is it a Noun (NP) or a Verb (VP)? Then, trace that head up to its governing phrase. If the PP is attached to the VP, the VP is the node that dictates that attachment. If you see a branch that seems to jump across levels without a clear head-to-governor link, that's your sign of a potential error—it's a misplaced attachment, or a structural anomaly.",
      "source": "target",
